    b.
        These microorganisms may be useful to the cow because they can break down plant cell walls, which are tough, allowing the cow's enzymes to access the nutrients (e.g. starch stored in the vacuole) stored within the plant cell. It is difficult and would likely be expensive for the cow to produce its own enzymes which digest the cell wall. So, those microorganisms form a symbiotic relationship with the cow.

    c.
        Since injecting GH into cows means you can obtain the same volume of milk from fewer cows, this may mean that farmers will have less cows. So, there will be less digestion-induced methane. Methane is a greenhouse gas, so it causes climate change, so if the aforementioned happens, climate change would indeed reduce.

        However, it may be that farmers will keep the same amount of cows and simply get more milk -- the aforementioned description of events assumes that supply of milk will exceed or is already exceeding demand so much so that price of milk would substantially drop and cause keeping the same amount of cows globally to be untenable. However, this is not given. In addition, GH may be expensive to produce or to safely inject; this would cause smaller farmers to be outcompeted, possibly increasing greenhouse gas emissions as food will have to be transported further from larger industrial farms. Also, we are not told whether GH production causes climate change. 

        In addition, GH may cause an increase in digestion, as GH stimulates growth, and you need energy to grow, and cows get their energy from digestion. If the decrease in amount of cows cannot offset any increase in digestion, climate change will not reduce.
