        Grey white = Gg

        G   g
      G GG  Gg
      g Gg  gg

      parent genotypes = Gg, Gg
      offspring genotypes = GG, Gg, gg
      offspring phenotypes = 25% white hair, 75% grey hair; 1 : 3

    c.
        The scientist could cross the mouse with a mouse with white hair. The mouse with white hair must be homozygous recessive, since white hair is recessive. If the mouse with grey hair is heterozygous, then one of the offspring will have white hair. If it is homozygous, none of the offspring will have white hair. Of course, a sufficient number of offspring must result from the cross to eliminate the effects of random chance.
    d?
        Most phenotypic features are controlled using multiple genes. For instance, height is controlled by more than one gene. In addition, oftentimes, non-coding genes around the gene also control phenotypic features.
