    b? How is chlorophyll removed?
        wear safety goggles
    c.
        Control the temperature of the leaf and keep it the same with and without light.
    d?
        Leaves have a layer of palisade cells called the palisade layer which have lots of chloroplasts which contain chlorophyll for photosynthesis. This layer is close to the top surface of the leaf so will receive light for photosynthesis. In addition, the spongy mesophyll has lots of pores to allow for good air-flow through the leaf, so carbon dioxide can be taken in and used in photosynthesis. Also, there are xylem to transport water into the leaf for use in photosynthesis.
11.
    a.
        i.
            Structure C is the cornea, which focuses the light most of the way. Structure A is the lens, which can change its shape to change how much light rays are bent. This allows it to become more convex to focus on light from a near object, or become less convex to focus on light from far away. Structure D is the ciliary muscles, which contract to reduce tension in the suspensory ligaments and to make the lens become more convex to focus on light from a near object. The lens has to be more convex to focus on a near object because those light rays will be diverging.

        ii.
            Structure B is the iris. The Iris Reflex occurs when the bright light is detected by the retina -> a nervous signal is sent to the brain -> a nervous signal is sent back to the eye/circular muscles -> Structure B constricts when there is bright light, lowering the amount of light that enters the eye, so the retina is exposed to less light, so is dimmer, so is not damaged.
        
    b.
        i.
            To break down any pathogens which may have gotten into the eye to prevent infection of the eyeball, as white blood cells cannot easily access the surface of the eye
        ii.
            So the eye is not irritated as pH7 is neutral, so other structures of the eye are not broken down/irritated by a basic/acidic liquid.
    